article.description: Playing their first game since Tuesday's seven-player trade, the Pacers missed a chance to reach .500 and suffered a 103-93 loss to the Cleveland Cavaliers.
article.headline: Pacers miss suspended Reggie Miller
article.linkText: New look not good enough for Pacers against Cavs
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A team in transition with three new players and no Reggie Miller, the Indiana Pacers couldn't click against the Cleveland Cavaliers.
Andre Miller

Andre Miller scored 27 points and Ricky Davis added 20 as the Cleveland Cavaliers spoiled the debut of the new-look Pacers with a 103-93 win Friday night. "We wanted to slide in quietly and slide out quietly while you're all still excited about the trade," Cleveland coach John Lucas said. The Cavaliers led by five early in the fourth before a 16-8 run put them ahead 95-82. Davis and Miller combined for 10 of those points as Cleveland ended a two-game losing streak. Wesley Person scored 17, Lamond Murray had 15 and Tyrone Hill added 10 points and 17 rebounds for Cleveland. The Pacers were playing their first game since acquiring Ron Artest, Ron Mercer, Brad Miller and Kevin Ollie from Chicago for Jalen Rose, Travis Best, Norm Richardson and a conditional second-round draft pick on Tuesday. The three shot a combined 20-for-27, while the rest of the team went 17-for-52. Artest started at shooting guard in place of Reggie Miller, who served a one-game suspension for throwing a punch at Philadelphia's Derrick Coleman. Artest scored 13 points on 6-for-7 shooting. He suffered a mild sprain of his left ankle early in the third quarter and played only five minutes in the second half. He appeared to hurt it after he made a layup and tumbled to the floor. He limped back on defense. "It was a freak accident," Artest said. "I was beginning to feel comfortable. I just wish I could have stayed in and helped a little longer." Brad Miller started at center, made four of his first seven shots and led the Pacers with 21 points before fouling out with under a minute left. Ollie scored a career-high 16 points. Pacers coach Isiah Thomas said the new acquisitions made a good first impression. "That's what I was looking for. Those guys came in and played really well for us," he said. "Artest had a good game going. When he got hurt, we didn't have enough left in the backcourt." Mercer is on the injured list with a knee injury. The Pacers had a chance to cut into the lead early in the fourth but missed four of five free throws, allowing Cleveland to push the lead to double digits. Brad Miller's acquisition let Jermaine O'Neal move back to his more natural power forward position. He scored 17 points on 7-for-21 shooting but missed his final six shots. Jonathan Bender added 12 points and Jamaal Tinsley had 12 assists for the Pacers, who have lost five of their last six games. Brad Miller scored 10 points in the first quarter as the Pacers took a 27-21 lead. Person hit three 3s in the opening minutes of the second as the Cavaliers pulled to 31-30. "I was about to take him out, then he hits those three 3's in a row, so I left him in," Lucas said. The lead was exchanged four times before Trajan Langdon hit a 3 to put Cleveland ahead for good, 43-41. Davis, Langdon and Zydrunas Ilgauskas came off the bench to go for 7-for-11 in the second and turn the game in Cleveland's favor. "It was a big stretch for us," Person said. "We came out flat to start the game, but we were able to have a big second quarter. It was just a matter of us hitting our shots and I think we played with a lot more intensity." Murray scored 11 points in the third, extending the lead to nine. A playoff berth may out of reach for the Cavaliers, but Lucas likes their progress. "It took us a long time get us playing like we're playing now, but we're there," he said. "Hopefully we can close out the year like that."

Game notes
Ollie had Rose's old locker, Miller had Best's, Artest took over former Pacer Derrick McKey's while Mercer used an unoccupied locker. ... Brad Miller has already bought a house. It was previously owned by Best. ...Reggie Miller and Rose had been the only Pacers to start every game. ...The Pacers made 19 of 27 free throws. ...Davis received a technical foul while Artest was called for a flagrant foul. ...Cleveland outrebounded Indiana 49-31. ...The Pacers missed all six 3-pointers, ending a streak of 91 straight games with at least one. ...Cleveland is 7-20 on the road.
